WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.900
So why don't we get started? So, I'm Omer Yilmaz.

2
00:00:03.980 --> 00:00:07.660
I'm a faculty member at the Koch Institute for Integrative Cancer Research, where

3
00:00:07.700 --> 00:00:11.300
my lab studies the effects of diet on stem cells in

4
00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:15.600
regeneration and colorectal cancer formation.

5
00:00:16.121 --> 00:00:19.760
And I'm also a gastrointestinal pathologist at the Beth Israel Deaconess

6
00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:23.680
Medical Center in Boston. And it's really a pleasure to chair

7
00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:28.440
today's session. We have a lineup of great speakers in

8
00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:32.500
Dr. Ruth Langley and Dr. Raymond

9
00:00:33.140 --> 00:00:33.660
Dubois.

10
00:00:34.660 --> 00:00:38.449
So today we'll talk about aspirin for the prevention and

11
00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:40.580
treatment of colorectal cancer, and this is

12
00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:42.440
a special session,

13
00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:45.340
in addition, because it honors

14
00:00:46.300 --> 00:00:50.220
the work and memory of Thomas Kensler, who

15
00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:54.170
was a pioneer in cancer chemoprevention, whose work bridged mechanistic

16
00:00:54.260 --> 00:00:57.880
toxicology and population-based clinical

17
00:00:58.020 --> 00:00:58.440
studies.

18
00:00:59.260 --> 00:01:02.860
And Tom, in addition to playing an important

19
00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:05.900
role in helping establish this field,

20
00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:10.430
he trained many of the individuals who went on to further

21
00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:14.380
develop the field. And he was a devoted mentor

22
00:01:14.420 --> 00:01:18.260
to generations of cancer prevention scientists, the achievement of

23
00:01:18.300 --> 00:01:22.220
which he was most proud of. So again, this session is dedicated to

24
00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:25.760
his memory, and I'd just like to call out to Dr.

25
00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:27.520
Nancy Davidson,

26
00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:32.300
Tom's wife. And Nancy, thank you so much for being here

27
00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:32.660
today.

28
00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:35.960
So

29
00:01:37.100 --> 00:01:40.160
decades of evidence across study designs converge on

30
00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:44.120
the same finding, which

31
00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:47.570
is aspirin lowers colorectal cancer incidence and

32
00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:48.290
mortality.

33
00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:52.120
And aspirin is one of the best supported, studied

34
00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:55.680
chemopreventive agents in oncology, which makes

35
00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:59.620
understanding its mechanism and its limitations important.

36
00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:02.120
And we've known for

37
00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:07.320
more than two decades, in the Rothwell pooled meta-analysis, for example, when

38
00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:11.340
aspirin is regularly taken by individuals at

39
00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:14.900
the age of 60, that aspirin reduces

40
00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:18.580
colorectal incidents on the order of 40%

41
00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:22.120
and colorectal cancer mortality by greater than

42
00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:25.820
50%. And this mean age of enrollment of 60 is important

43
00:02:25.840 --> 00:02:29.420
because I'm going to, in my own presentation, talk

44
00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:33.460
about an interesting paradox that occurs when aspirin

45
00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:37.440
is started later in life, namely in patients that

46
00:02:37.540 --> 00:02:41.320
average 70 years of age. And aspirin mediates

47
00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:44.460
its many effects with respect to suppressing colorectal

48
00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:48.200
cancer through multiple mechanisms.

49
00:02:48.829 --> 00:02:52.640
And it's believed that aspirin, by suppressing prostaglandin

50
00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:56.640
E2 in epithelial cells, as well as in adjacent niche

51
00:02:56.700 --> 00:03:00.660
cells such as immune cells and in platelets, plays a key role in

52
00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:04.400
regulating both the initiation and aspects of colorectal

53
00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:07.120
cancer progression and metastasis.

54
00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:09.620
In addition to a lot of the

55
00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:11.620
patient

56
00:03:12.620 --> 00:03:16.160
clinical trial data, we've known for more than 20 years that in

57
00:03:16.260 --> 00:03:20.120
preclinical models such as in the ApcMin model,

58
00:03:20.180 --> 00:03:24.160
which is a preclinical model for familial adenomatous polyposis, where

59
00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:24.750
these mice,

60
00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:29.400
within a few months of life, develop multiple adenomas.

61
00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:35.300
When one deletes the gene prostaglandin synthase 1, or

62
00:03:35.340 --> 00:03:39.100
COX-1, or prostaglandin synthase 2, COX-2, in this

63
00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:42.880
preclinical model, one dramatically dampens adenoma

64
00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:45.880
formation throughout the small intestine and colon.

65
00:03:46.440 --> 00:03:46.740
And

66
00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:49.460
one of our speakers today, Dr.

67
00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:53.580
Raymond Dubois, has really been a leader in understanding how

68
00:03:53.620 --> 00:03:57.560
prostaglandins early on in the intestinal and colonic

69
00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:01.440
epithelium, how prostaglandins mediate this by binding to

70
00:04:01.480 --> 00:04:05.040
their receptor and engaging pathways that are important

71
00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:08.460
for survival, proliferation, invasion,

72
00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:10.320
angiogenesis, and other

73
00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:15.020
mechanisms. And I look forward to Ray's talk

74
00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:19.000
later this morning. In addition to being

75
00:04:19.060 --> 00:04:23.000
a potent suppressor of early dysplasia in the

76
00:04:23.060 --> 00:04:23.460
colon,

77
00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:28.000
aspirin can also play an important role in colorectal progression.

78
00:04:28.580 --> 00:04:31.860
So work from Andy Chan, Charlie Fuchs, and

79
00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:35.700
Shuji Ojino have demonstrated

80
00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:39.580
that PIK3CA mutations in exon 9 and exon

81
00:04:39.740 --> 00:04:43.580
20 can serve as a biomarker of response for aspirin.

82
00:04:43.620 --> 00:04:47.180
When aspirin is started early on after diagnosis,

83
00:04:47.700 --> 00:04:51.560
aspirin use suppresses or decreases the probability of death

84
00:04:51.960 --> 00:04:54.960
from colorectal cancer in patients that harbor these

85
00:04:55.020 --> 00:04:58.780
mutations compared to colorectal cancers

86
00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:02.780
that are wild type in PIK3CA

87
00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:06.960
mutations. And Dr. Ruth Langley will talk

88
00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:10.560
more about this in her session after mine.

89
00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:16.320
So I'd like to end my introduction with a bit of

90
00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:19.280
more controversial or paradoxical data.

91
00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:23.140
Which is, I mentioned to you in the Rothwell pooled randomized

92
00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:25.920
control trial that when aspirin is started in

93
00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:29.580
patients that are on average 60 years of age and taken

94
00:05:29.620 --> 00:05:33.240
regularly, that leads to a reduction in colorectal cancer

95
00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:36.980
incidence and mortality. In the ASPREE trial, on average,

96
00:05:37.660 --> 00:05:38.200
patients

97
00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:42.400
with an average age of 70 who regularly took aspirin,

98
00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:46.580
interestingly, these patients, within a short period of four years, started to

99
00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:50.280
diverge from their placebo group, where there was an increase in death

100
00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:54.300
related to cancer. So why is that?

101
00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:57.990
This really raises a paradox that I'd like to explore in my

102
00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:02.040
presentation, which is, does aspirin have opposing effects on cancer

103
00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:06.020
initiation versus metastasis?And the work

104
00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:08.020
that I'm going to talk about today is unpublished.

105
00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:11.900
Actually, it's the first time that I'm talking about it, so I apologize if it's a

106
00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:15.880
bit rough around the edges. But it's about understanding the

107
00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:19.870
paradoxical effect of aspirin on colorectal cancer prevention and

108
00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:23.060
metastasis. The work was led by a very talented

109
00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:26.540
MD-PhD student in my lab, Joseph Sedlock, in

110
00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:30.040
collaboration with Dr. Swagata Goswami and

111
00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:34.160
Burak Yildiz. And this was a collaboration between my lab and Andrew

112
00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:37.619
Chan's lab at the Mass General Hospital.

113
00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:42.060
So, my disclosures per ACR

114
00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:43.300
rules.

115
00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:47.820
So what do we know about aspirin and cancer

116
00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:51.689
metastasis? So work published last year by

117
00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:52.830
Yang et al. in "Nature,"

118
00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:57.550
proposed that aspirin reduces metastatic initiation and seeding

119
00:06:57.580 --> 00:07:01.400
by limiting platelet-derived thromboxane A2, which

120
00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:04.450
inhibits T cell function. And

121
00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:09.070
we like to think about metastasis as having many phases, but two important

122
00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:12.720
phases of metastasis are seeding of a distant organ

123
00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:16.260
and then the outgrowth of those seeds into established

124
00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:20.340
metastatic lesions. And what Yang and colleagues showed

125
00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:24.660
last year using a B16 melanoma lung metastasis

126
00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:28.360
model is that when these mice were given aspirin, this

127
00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:32.000
reduced the number of micromets and nodules in the lung,

128
00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:32.880
and that this

129
00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:37.460
suppression could be rescued by treating these mice with a

130
00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:41.390
thromboxane A2 analog. And mechanistically, they

131
00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:44.790
propose that thromboxane A2 can

132
00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:48.400
activate this protein in T cells called R-GEF1.

133
00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:52.320
And using a genetic approach where they conditionally ablate

134
00:07:52.440 --> 00:07:55.720
R-GEF1 in T cells of mice, this

135
00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:59.470
essentially nullifies the effects of aspirin and

136
00:07:59.500 --> 00:08:03.280
thromboxane A2 on metastasis. So this was

137
00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:06.960
important insight regarding a potential suppressive role that

138
00:08:06.970 --> 00:08:10.500
aspirin plays in the early steps of metastatic seeding to

139
00:08:10.540 --> 00:08:14.179
the lung. But what about

140
00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:17.860
aspirin's effects on established metastases, that is

141
00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:22.000
metastatic outgrowth? So coming back to the ASPREE

142
00:08:22.080 --> 00:08:26.060
trial where aspirin used in 70-year-old

143
00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:29.170
individuals over time increases cancer mortality.

144
00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:33.581
Again, notice that these curves start to diverge between aspirin and placebo

145
00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:38.220
at about four years, which is really too rapid for new

146
00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:41.650
cancer initiation and spread throughout the body.

147
00:08:41.850 --> 00:08:45.420
It's more consistent with the possibility that

148
00:08:45.500 --> 00:08:49.320
aspirin use may be accelerating the outgrowth of preexisting

149
00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:51.640
occult metastatic disease.

150
00:08:52.620 --> 00:08:54.600
So why was this trial such an outlier?

151
00:08:54.680 --> 00:08:57.620
Does aspirin promote the growth of preexisting

152
00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:01.240
micrometastases? So if one digs into the data from

153
00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:04.980
McNeill and colleagues from ASPREE, one finds that

154
00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:08.620
aspirin appears to promote metastasis across multiple cancer

155
00:09:08.720 --> 00:09:12.580
types in ASPREE. While there wasn't a notable

156
00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:16.570
effect in Stage 1 through 3, in Stage 4, where there's metastatic

157
00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:17.600
disease, aspirin

158
00:09:18.420 --> 00:09:19.640
accelerated

159
00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:22.480
cancer death in these patients.

160
00:09:23.300 --> 00:09:27.260
So what happens to patients with colorectal cancer in ASPREE on

161
00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:31.220
aspirin after their diagnoses? So in unpublished work

162
00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:31.620
by

163
00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:36.060
Andy Chan's group at the MGH, they find that in colorectal

164
00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:39.940
cancer patients with Stage 1 to 3 disease, there's a

165
00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.400
trend towards aspirin actually

166
00:09:43.820 --> 00:09:47.680
improving overall survival. But interestingly, in Stage

167
00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:51.480
4 colorectal cancer patients, aspirin increases overall

168
00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:55.320
mortality by greater than twofold, suggesting that aspirin's

169
00:09:55.340 --> 00:09:59.100
effect on mortality after colorectal cancer diagnosis

170
00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:03.300
is stage dependent. So again, this really sets up

171
00:10:03.340 --> 00:10:06.780
our aspirin paradox for colorectal cancer, where there's a

172
00:10:07.400 --> 00:10:10.680
lot of preclinical and patient data suggesting that

173
00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:14.520
aspirin in young or middle adulthood

174
00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:18.100
suppresses colorectal cancer incidence and improves

175
00:10:18.580 --> 00:10:22.520
overall mortality rates. But aspirin also increases

176
00:10:22.560 --> 00:10:26.520
colorectal cancer mortality in those patients with Stage 4

177
00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:30.090
metastatic disease. How can one reconcile these

178
00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:31.520
paradoxical findings?

179
00:10:32.340 --> 00:10:36.080
So, this really leads into my lab's expertise, where we have a lot of

180
00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:39.500
expertise in modeling physiologic metastasis

181
00:10:40.340 --> 00:10:44.160
in colorectal cancer, where we can take patient-derived or

182
00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:47.260
mouse-derived organoids, these are primary cells,

183
00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:52.120
and then we can engineer in cancer-causing mutations in the

184
00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:55.560
tumor suppressor genes, APC, p53, and the

185
00:10:55.600 --> 00:10:58.380
proto-oncogene K-RAS. This genotype of

186
00:10:58.420 --> 00:11:02.240
APC-K-RAS-p53, I'm going to call by short

187
00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:06.200
AKP. And this AKP genotype in colorectal cancer

188
00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:09.600
is found in up to 50% of colon cancer

189
00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:13.680
patients. And then we can really interrogate metastasis by

190
00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:17.340
performing two types of transplantation assays.

191
00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:18.400
In the first

192
00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:22.740
assay, we can transplant these AKT colorectal cancer

193
00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:25.560
organoids into the colon of recipient mice.

194
00:11:26.220 --> 00:11:29.640
After a few weeks, these mice not only develop primary

195
00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:33.580
tumors in the colon, but a subset of these mice go on to develop

196
00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:37.420
metastatic disease in the liver, the primary site of

197
00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:39.620
metastasis for colon cancer.

198
00:11:40.480 --> 00:11:44.120
In parallel to this type of orthotopic transplantation system,

199
00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:48.450
we can also transplant these AKP colorectal cancer organoids

200
00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:52.020
in equal cell numbers into the portal circulation, which is the

201
00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:55.560
vasculature that empties into the liver.

202
00:11:55.660 --> 00:11:59.180
And this model allows us to assay metastasis

203
00:11:59.190 --> 00:12:03.180
directly, where initiation of these metastatic lesions is

204
00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:06.880
essentially a measure of metastatic establishment

205
00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:10.836
and outgrowth.So what do we find? So when we

206
00:12:10.856 --> 00:12:14.836
transplant these AKP organoids into the colon of mice and then

207
00:12:14.856 --> 00:12:18.756
perform transcriptional analysis on the metastatic lesions

208
00:12:19.156 --> 00:12:22.836
relative to their primary counterparts, one interesting

209
00:12:22.916 --> 00:12:26.196
observation that we made is that the metastatic lesions

210
00:12:26.236 --> 00:12:30.216
downregulate prostaglandin synthase 1, a key enzyme in

211
00:12:30.256 --> 00:12:32.716
the production of prostaglandin E2.

212
00:12:33.356 --> 00:12:37.196
And not only does one see downregulation of prostaglandin E2,

213
00:12:37.296 --> 00:12:41.295
but when one measures prostaglandin E2 in organoids derived

214
00:12:41.316 --> 00:12:44.856
from these metastatic lesions versus

215
00:12:44.896 --> 00:12:48.676
organoids from the primary site, again, one finds that the metastatic

216
00:12:48.736 --> 00:12:52.156
organoids are less capable of generating prostaglandin

217
00:12:52.216 --> 00:12:55.176
E2 compared to the control primary.

218
00:12:55.216 --> 00:12:59.196
Again, consistent with the trends that we're observing in our

219
00:12:59.496 --> 00:13:02.976
gene changes in PTGS1. But

220
00:13:03.996 --> 00:13:07.576
one could ask, is this some type of idiosyncrasy of the mouse model we're using?

221
00:13:07.606 --> 00:13:11.596
Is it generalizable to patients? To gain insight

222
00:13:11.616 --> 00:13:14.876
into this, we analyzed patients with matched primary

223
00:13:15.276 --> 00:13:19.216
colorectal cancer and liver metastases where RNA

224
00:13:19.276 --> 00:13:23.216
sequencing was performed. And again, analogous to what

225
00:13:23.256 --> 00:13:26.916
we observed in our mouse AKP model, we find that

226
00:13:26.956 --> 00:13:30.876
PTGS1 was downregulated in the liver met compared

227
00:13:30.976 --> 00:13:34.316
to the primary tumor, and no change in

228
00:13:34.376 --> 00:13:38.296
PTGS2. Again, consistent with what we were observing in our mouse

229
00:13:38.396 --> 00:13:38.716
model.

230
00:13:39.896 --> 00:13:43.736
So this then leads to the question: Does prostaglandin

231
00:13:43.816 --> 00:13:47.216
E2 play a functional role in colorectal cancer

232
00:13:47.616 --> 00:13:48.456
metastasis?

233
00:13:49.996 --> 00:13:53.956
And again, we took advantage of our genome editing toolbox where

234
00:13:53.996 --> 00:13:57.216
we could manipulate prostaglandin E2 levels

235
00:13:57.276 --> 00:14:00.016
genetically in our AKP organoids.

236
00:14:00.076 --> 00:14:03.916
So we generated organoids that were deficient in prostaglandin

237
00:14:04.016 --> 00:14:07.476
synthase 1 and 2, and this corresponds to a reduction in

238
00:14:07.556 --> 00:14:10.176
PGE2 in data that I'm not showing you.

239
00:14:10.716 --> 00:14:13.956
And then conversely, we can delete the gene

240
00:14:14.276 --> 00:14:17.776
HPGD, which codes for 15-prostaglandin

241
00:14:18.316 --> 00:14:22.276
dehydrogenase, an enzyme that degrades prostaglandin E2.

242
00:14:22.736 --> 00:14:26.456
Thus, loss of HPGD leads to an increase in

243
00:14:26.496 --> 00:14:30.056
prostaglandin E2, which we were able to verify in organoid

244
00:14:30.136 --> 00:14:33.696
assays. So now that we have a toolkit where we can genetically

245
00:14:33.756 --> 00:14:37.436
manipulate prostaglandin E2 levels, specifically

246
00:14:37.856 --> 00:14:41.236
in tumor cells, we can ask the question: What are the effects of

247
00:14:41.256 --> 00:14:44.576
colorectal cancer-produced prostaglandins in the two

248
00:14:44.636 --> 00:14:47.076
metastasis models that I described to you?

249
00:14:47.956 --> 00:14:51.196
So in the first set of transplantations, we transplanted

250
00:14:51.256 --> 00:14:54.916
AKP or AKP PTGS1,2

251
00:14:54.956 --> 00:14:58.676
deficient organoids, which again are low in prostaglandin

252
00:14:58.796 --> 00:15:02.756
E2 levels. In terms of primary colon

253
00:15:03.196 --> 00:15:06.836
growth, we found no change in greatest

254
00:15:06.876 --> 00:15:09.656
dimension or in mass of these primary tumors.

255
00:15:10.216 --> 00:15:14.136
But interestingly, when we looked at metastasis, we observed,

256
00:15:14.176 --> 00:15:16.536
again, consistent with what Yang et al.

257
00:15:16.816 --> 00:15:20.376
published last year, that dampening prostaglandin E2 in the

258
00:15:20.476 --> 00:15:23.335
primary tumor resulted in fewer

259
00:15:24.336 --> 00:15:25.576
metastatic lesions,

260
00:15:26.456 --> 00:15:30.176
in this case, in the liver, where the control AKP gave

261
00:15:30.216 --> 00:15:34.036
rise to many more mets per recipient

262
00:15:34.096 --> 00:15:37.686
compared to the AKP COX-1, COX-2 deficient

263
00:15:37.696 --> 00:15:40.756
organoids. But it's not that none of the

264
00:15:40.816 --> 00:15:43.536
PTGS1,2 deficient organoids

265
00:15:44.716 --> 00:15:48.236
didn't give rise to mets. Clearly, some animals developed

266
00:15:48.256 --> 00:15:52.176
metastatic lesions in the liver. So we then wanted to analyze

267
00:15:52.256 --> 00:15:55.696
what effect loss of PTGS1 within the hepatic

268
00:15:55.716 --> 00:15:58.296
parenchyma had on metastatic outgrowth.

269
00:15:58.876 --> 00:15:59.236
And

270
00:16:00.176 --> 00:16:03.836
I should just mention that our AKP organoids also harbor

271
00:16:04.316 --> 00:16:08.096
a tdTomato fluorescent marker that permits us to carefully

272
00:16:10.016 --> 00:16:13.196
identify and measure the size of these lesions.

273
00:16:13.236 --> 00:16:16.876
So here we're looking at the livers from mice that received AKP or

274
00:16:16.936 --> 00:16:19.676
AKP PTGS1,2 deficient organoids.

275
00:16:20.196 --> 00:16:23.696
So the AKP recipients had more

276
00:16:23.756 --> 00:16:27.346
metastatic lesions, but that tended to be much smaller in

277
00:16:27.376 --> 00:16:31.016
size compared to the hepatic parenchyma that

278
00:16:31.036 --> 00:16:34.596
received PTGS1,2 deficient AKP organoids.

279
00:16:34.936 --> 00:16:38.496
And here we're looking at the size of these organoids on a log10 plot,

280
00:16:38.536 --> 00:16:42.076
and these PTGS1,2 deficient

281
00:16:42.276 --> 00:16:46.196
cancer cells were about tenfold greater in size in the

282
00:16:46.236 --> 00:16:48.696
liver compared to their control counterparts.

283
00:16:49.396 --> 00:16:52.996
So does aspirin treatment mimic the effects

284
00:16:53.096 --> 00:16:57.056
of genetically ablating PTGS1,2 in these AKP

285
00:16:57.136 --> 00:17:00.596
organoids? So again, we transplanted AKP and

286
00:17:00.656 --> 00:17:04.456
AKP PTGS1,2 deficient organoids into the

287
00:17:04.517 --> 00:17:08.076
colon and now treated these mice with equivalents of low-dose

288
00:17:08.156 --> 00:17:11.816
aspirin. And just focusing on here where we're looking at

289
00:17:11.896 --> 00:17:15.376
primary tumor prostaglandin E2, again,

290
00:17:15.696 --> 00:17:19.176
consistent with genetic ablation of PTGS1,2,

291
00:17:19.616 --> 00:17:23.247
aspirin treatment reduces primary tumor PGE2 levels.

292
00:17:23.757 --> 00:17:27.596
And again, if we now look at metastatic outgrowth in the liver in the

293
00:17:27.636 --> 00:17:31.536
subsets of mice that develop metastatic disease, consistent with

294
00:17:31.576 --> 00:17:35.056
genetic loss, aspirin treatment also increased the

295
00:17:35.136 --> 00:17:38.036
size of these metastatic lesions in the liver,

296
00:17:38.776 --> 00:17:42.016
indicating that aspirin increases the size of colorectal

297
00:17:42.616 --> 00:17:46.476
cancer liver metastases. So what happens

298
00:17:46.536 --> 00:17:50.396
if one bypasses the primary tumor and now places equivalent

299
00:17:50.456 --> 00:17:54.396
numbers of colorectal cancer cells directly into the portal

300
00:17:54.476 --> 00:17:57.956
circulation to seed the liver? So here we

301
00:17:58.476 --> 00:18:00.656
transplanted AKP and our AKP

302
00:18:00.756 --> 00:18:04.636
PTGS1,2 deficient organoids. And what we

303
00:18:04.676 --> 00:18:05.786
now find is that

304
00:18:07.376 --> 00:18:10.826
downregulation of PGE2 reduces the number and

305
00:18:10.956 --> 00:18:14.396
size of these metastatic lesions, and

306
00:18:14.756 --> 00:18:18.056
loss of PTGS1,2 dramatically increases the numbers and

307
00:18:18.156 --> 00:18:21.928
sizeAgain, here we've quantified numbers of liver mets,

308
00:18:22.008 --> 00:18:25.908
which is analogous to what we find if we were to measure size, that there's a

309
00:18:25.968 --> 00:18:29.128
notable increase in the size and numbers of

310
00:18:29.748 --> 00:18:33.728
metastatic lesions in the liver when we place these PTGS1-2

311
00:18:33.748 --> 00:18:37.228
deficient AKP organoids into the portal circulation.

312
00:18:38.028 --> 00:18:41.648
So the fact that prostaglandins seem to inhibit metastatic

313
00:18:41.748 --> 00:18:45.408
outgrowth raised the possibility that perhaps

314
00:18:45.448 --> 00:18:49.308
prostaglandins themselves can treat colorectal cancer

315
00:18:49.708 --> 00:18:52.988
liver mets in patients that harbor potentially

316
00:18:53.048 --> 00:18:57.028
micrometastatic lesions. To address this, we took advantage of

317
00:18:57.068 --> 00:19:00.958
the other set of organoids that we engineered in the lab, the AKP and

318
00:19:01.008 --> 00:19:04.598
AKPHPGD deficient organoids. Remember,

319
00:19:05.168 --> 00:19:08.928
these organoids are high in PGE2

320
00:19:08.968 --> 00:19:12.508
levels. And when we transplant these into the portal circulation,

321
00:19:12.968 --> 00:19:16.468
consistent with the notion that prostaglandins inhibit metastatic

322
00:19:16.548 --> 00:19:18.428
outgrowth, we find that these

323
00:19:19.648 --> 00:19:23.548
HPGD deficient organoids give rise to fewer and

324
00:19:23.648 --> 00:19:26.548
smaller metastatic lesions in the

325
00:19:26.588 --> 00:19:30.128
liver. In addition to taking a genetic approach, we also took a

326
00:19:30.208 --> 00:19:33.688
pharmacological approach where we treated these

327
00:19:33.888 --> 00:19:37.808
recipient mice with a 15 prostaglandin dehydrogenase

328
00:19:37.868 --> 00:19:39.387
inhibitor, this molecule called

329
00:19:39.508 --> 00:19:43.388
SW033291. So here we

330
00:19:43.408 --> 00:19:46.628
transplanted AKP organoids into the portal circulation,

331
00:19:47.108 --> 00:19:50.848
treated these mice with the 15 PGDH

332
00:19:50.908 --> 00:19:53.948
inhibitor. And what we found here, analogous to the

333
00:19:53.968 --> 00:19:57.868
AKPHPGD deficient organoids, is that treatment with this

334
00:19:57.908 --> 00:19:58.648
antagonist

335
00:19:59.888 --> 00:20:02.548
reduced the number and size of these organoids.

336
00:20:02.608 --> 00:20:06.388
And here's just representative images from one of these

337
00:20:06.648 --> 00:20:10.628
recipients from each group, where in the vehicle treatment, one has greater numbers

338
00:20:10.668 --> 00:20:13.788
of organoids that are larger in size, and treatment with the

339
00:20:13.808 --> 00:20:17.748
inhibitor reduces number and size of these metastatic

340
00:20:17.788 --> 00:20:21.448
lesions. So what is the mechanism by which prostaglandin

341
00:20:21.768 --> 00:20:25.588
is mediating these anti-metastatic outgrowth effects in the

342
00:20:25.628 --> 00:20:29.448
liver? Could there be a role for the immune system in this process, given the

343
00:20:29.467 --> 00:20:33.388
interesting findings from Yang et al. last year?

344
00:20:34.128 --> 00:20:34.368
So

345
00:20:35.208 --> 00:20:38.888
we wanted to turn our attention to T cells and

346
00:20:38.968 --> 00:20:42.668
NK cells, given the important role that these populations play

347
00:20:43.148 --> 00:20:47.048
in cancer immunology. So in data that I've shown you, we repeated our

348
00:20:47.088 --> 00:20:50.148
transplantation where we transplanted AKP and

349
00:20:50.188 --> 00:20:53.668
AKPPTGS12 deficient organoids.

350
00:20:54.008 --> 00:20:55.768
Again, these are low in prostaglandins.

351
00:20:56.208 --> 00:20:59.828
And in immunocompetent recipients, which have a normal

352
00:21:00.408 --> 00:21:04.328
immune system that's syngeneic with the organoids that we're transplanting,

353
00:21:04.708 --> 00:21:07.668
we find that PTGS12, when

354
00:21:08.188 --> 00:21:12.168
transplanted into the portal circulation, increases the number and size

355
00:21:12.488 --> 00:21:15.768
of these metastatic lesions. But now what happens when one

356
00:21:15.828 --> 00:21:19.508
transplants these organoids into mice that lack a

357
00:21:19.588 --> 00:21:23.488
functional immune system? In this case, we use NOD/SCID gamma mice, which

358
00:21:23.528 --> 00:21:26.718
have dysfunctional T, B, and NK cells.

359
00:21:27.128 --> 00:21:30.968
And in this recipient model, where adaptive

360
00:21:30.988 --> 00:21:34.868
immune cells as well as NK cells are compromised, now this difference

361
00:21:34.908 --> 00:21:38.688
between the seeding of the liver disappears, indicating that

362
00:21:39.068 --> 00:21:42.748
likely one of these immune cell populations is an important mediator

363
00:21:43.228 --> 00:21:46.608
of the anti-metastatic outgrowth effects of

364
00:21:46.668 --> 00:21:50.648
prostaglandin. So which population is at play here?

365
00:21:50.828 --> 00:21:54.428
So we went ahead and depleted either CD8

366
00:21:54.468 --> 00:21:58.068
positive T cells with antibodies or NK cells with

367
00:21:58.148 --> 00:22:02.018
antibodies. And we transplanted in our AKP and

368
00:22:02.068 --> 00:22:03.537
AKPHPGDH

369
00:22:05.248 --> 00:22:09.048
deficient organoids, which again are high in prostaglandin and which should have an

370
00:22:09.088 --> 00:22:12.608
inhibitory effect on metastatic seeding and outgrowth when

371
00:22:12.668 --> 00:22:14.528
injected into the portal circulation.

372
00:22:15.108 --> 00:22:18.668
And what we found here is when we depleted CD8 positive T cells,

373
00:22:19.188 --> 00:22:22.958
again, the HPGD compared to the control were less

374
00:22:23.008 --> 00:22:26.008
capable of forming these metastatic lesions.

375
00:22:26.288 --> 00:22:29.558
Depletion of CD8 positive T cells trended but

376
00:22:30.588 --> 00:22:34.528
didn't significantly impact these effects of tumor-derived

377
00:22:34.537 --> 00:22:38.128
prostaglandin. What happens when one now depletes the

378
00:22:38.248 --> 00:22:41.968
NK cells? When we deplete NK cells and now repeat these

379
00:22:42.048 --> 00:22:45.788
transplantations, we now find that depletion of NK cells

380
00:22:46.668 --> 00:22:50.308
really prevents the inhibitory effects that tumor-derived

381
00:22:50.668 --> 00:22:53.548
prostaglandins have on establishing

382
00:22:55.068 --> 00:22:57.028
and enabling metastatic outgrowth.

383
00:22:58.448 --> 00:23:02.348
So how do prostaglandins trigger NK cell-mediated anti-tumor

384
00:23:02.388 --> 00:23:05.968
immunity? We turned our attention to the tumor microenvironment.

385
00:23:06.968 --> 00:23:10.888
And we were really interested in this particular component

386
00:23:10.988 --> 00:23:14.218
of the liver microenvironment called these hepatic stellate cells or

387
00:23:14.408 --> 00:23:18.348
HSCs, because a lot is known about these HSCs, and they play an important

388
00:23:18.388 --> 00:23:21.808
role in regulating the immune milieu in the

389
00:23:22.248 --> 00:23:26.008
liver. The other reason why we were interested in studying HSCs is

390
00:23:26.068 --> 00:23:29.768
because we knew from spatial transcriptomics data, where we

391
00:23:29.808 --> 00:23:33.788
performed spatial transcriptomics in mice that were

392
00:23:34.088 --> 00:23:38.028
transplanted with AKP organoids and treated with our 15

393
00:23:38.068 --> 00:23:42.048
prostaglandin synthase inhibitor, the SW molecule, that

394
00:23:42.058 --> 00:23:45.588
compared to vehicle treated where we have large metastatic lesions,

395
00:23:46.048 --> 00:23:49.808
shown here in green, with many hepatic stellate cells, shown here in

396
00:23:49.828 --> 00:23:52.284
yellow, when we treat with our... our

397
00:23:52.504 --> 00:23:56.344
15-PGDH inhibitor, now the metastases

398
00:23:56.364 --> 00:24:00.284
shrink, and we have fewer HSCs. And we can validate

399
00:24:00.344 --> 00:24:04.044
that this reduction in HSCs doesn't only occur at the transcriptional

400
00:24:04.104 --> 00:24:07.984
level. If we use flow cytometry to enumerate these HSCs, again,

401
00:24:08.043 --> 00:24:11.764
we find that after treatment with our inhibitor, there's a notable

402
00:24:12.084 --> 00:24:15.984
several-fold reduction in the percentage of HSCs in this liver.

403
00:24:16.064 --> 00:24:19.424
So this really indicated that perhaps these

404
00:24:19.604 --> 00:24:23.124
HSCs might be mediating some of the anti-tumor

405
00:24:23.164 --> 00:24:26.584
immunity effects of tumor-derived prostaglandins.

406
00:24:27.084 --> 00:24:30.744
So do HSCs mediate these effects of PG2 in

407
00:24:30.814 --> 00:24:34.584
colorectal cancer metastasis? To address this, we generated a

408
00:24:34.624 --> 00:24:38.374
mouse model that enabled us to selectively

409
00:24:38.404 --> 00:24:42.384
deplete HSCs in the liver parenchyma.

410
00:24:42.844 --> 00:24:46.824
So here we're staining with a marker of these HSCs, shown here in red.

411
00:24:46.884 --> 00:24:50.804
So in the control liver, HSCs are quite abundant and spaced out

412
00:24:50.844 --> 00:24:54.824
throughout the hepatic lobule. And in our diphtheria toxin model, where

413
00:24:54.864 --> 00:24:58.764
we can selectively deplete these HSCs, we see a

414
00:24:58.824 --> 00:25:00.144
nice reduction of HSCs.

415
00:25:01.004 --> 00:25:04.564
So what happens now if we transplant our AKP

416
00:25:04.744 --> 00:25:08.264
organoids into livers that lack these HSCs?

417
00:25:08.764 --> 00:25:11.824
So here we transplanted again our AKP and AKPH

418
00:25:11.904 --> 00:25:15.844
PGD-deficient organoids, which loss of HPGD

419
00:25:15.864 --> 00:25:19.624
leads to high prostaglandins, which suppresses metastatic outgrowth.

420
00:25:20.004 --> 00:25:23.764
When we now ablate HSCs, we nullify the

421
00:25:23.784 --> 00:25:27.364
inhibitory effects that prostaglandins have on metastatic

422
00:25:27.444 --> 00:25:31.084
outgrowth. So I'd just like to summarize and say that

423
00:25:31.104 --> 00:25:34.914
aspirin reduces prostaglandin E2 in liver mets by driving

424
00:25:34.944 --> 00:25:37.834
metastatic outgrowth through what we propose is this

425
00:25:38.004 --> 00:25:41.964
HSC NK cell circuit. We think this is an important step

426
00:25:42.004 --> 00:25:45.844
in resolving the aspirin paradox, where the evidence

427
00:25:45.884 --> 00:25:49.564
is clear. Aspirin chemoprevention reduces

428
00:25:49.604 --> 00:25:52.764
PG2-mediated tumor initiation in the colon.

429
00:25:53.164 --> 00:25:54.064
And in the liver,

430
00:25:55.004 --> 00:25:58.904
in response to metastatic seeding, by reducing PG2

431
00:25:58.924 --> 00:26:02.184
in the liver, aspirin permits micrometastatic outgrowth via

432
00:26:02.384 --> 00:26:05.174
HSC-mediated NK suppression,

433
00:26:06.464 --> 00:26:10.004
a potential mechanism in the elderly that may have higher rates of

434
00:26:10.364 --> 00:26:12.244
micrometastatic occult disease.

435
00:26:12.764 --> 00:26:16.444
So we're proposing that prostaglandin from micromets

436
00:26:16.824 --> 00:26:20.684
are suppressing hepatic stellate cells, which are known to make

437
00:26:20.704 --> 00:26:24.284
chemokines such as CXCL12 that are known to suppress

438
00:26:24.424 --> 00:26:28.164
NK cell biology, where NK cells themselves can

439
00:26:28.264 --> 00:26:29.544
then inhibit

440
00:26:30.164 --> 00:26:33.964
micrometastatic outgrowth. And we're

441
00:26:34.004 --> 00:26:37.264
now currently working on trying to understand how

442
00:26:37.344 --> 00:26:41.124
CXCL12 is doing this, and could there be other HSC-derived

443
00:26:41.204 --> 00:26:44.704
factors that are contributing to these suppressive effects of

444
00:26:44.864 --> 00:26:48.564
HSCs. So with that, I'd just like to thank the members of our

445
00:26:48.584 --> 00:26:52.204
laboratory, including our collaborators Andy Chan, David

446
00:26:52.264 --> 00:26:56.244
Drew at the Mass General, and I think we have three minutes for questions.

447
00:27:02.404 --> 00:27:04.884
So for questions for all the sessions, feel free to

448
00:27:05.804 --> 00:27:07.964
please use the microphones

449
00:27:10.324 --> 00:27:10.964
if possible.

450
00:27:20.804 --> 00:27:24.404
Hi, John Burn, Newcastle. That was amazing, and I

451
00:27:24.444 --> 00:27:27.684
imagine like the rest of the audience, I'm struggling to fully absorb it.

452
00:27:28.264 --> 00:27:32.144
But it does make sense. It clearly explains the paradox that you referred

453
00:27:32.224 --> 00:27:32.404
to.

454
00:27:33.544 --> 00:27:37.164
The other dimension that I struggle with is the

455
00:27:37.224 --> 00:27:40.694
question of apoptosis and where that plays in all of this.

456
00:27:40.933 --> 00:27:44.924
And I just wonder whether-- And we know from the work of my colleagues

457
00:27:44.964 --> 00:27:48.344
in Newcastle that knocking out mitochondrial function allows tumors to

458
00:27:48.384 --> 00:27:49.644
progress, and that

459
00:27:50.604 --> 00:27:54.504
there is a logical argument, since salicylates promote apoptosis

460
00:27:54.524 --> 00:27:57.564
in plants, that they may well play a similar role in humans.

461
00:27:58.124 --> 00:28:01.944
So my simple question is, is that an aspect that you have been able to

462
00:28:01.984 --> 00:28:05.744
look at in terms of apoptotic bodies, and does that play into this story

463
00:28:05.904 --> 00:28:09.844
as well as part of what you've just been

464
00:28:09.904 --> 00:28:10.354
describing?

465
00:28:11.104 --> 00:28:14.324
I think there could be many

466
00:28:14.364 --> 00:28:18.064
contributors to the phenotype that I described.

467
00:28:18.264 --> 00:28:21.344
We think anti-cancer immunity is one role for

468
00:28:21.484 --> 00:28:25.244
prostaglandins in micromets. It'd be interesting to see,

469
00:28:25.684 --> 00:28:29.384
and we haven't done this experiment, we should do it, how loss of prostaglandin

470
00:28:29.444 --> 00:28:32.364
E2 or elevation of prostaglandin E2

471
00:28:32.904 --> 00:28:36.724
stimulates the growth of these micromets directly by looking at

472
00:28:36.744 --> 00:28:40.604
proliferation, et cetera. Whether it's a causal or it's

473
00:28:40.644 --> 00:28:44.334
occurring through HSCs and NK cells is

474
00:28:44.384 --> 00:28:48.124
something that we would need to test, but we have the mouse models to test this.

475
00:28:48.624 --> 00:28:52.364
Clearly in the primary tumor, work done by Ray and many others have shown that

476
00:28:52.444 --> 00:28:55.264
prostaglandins stimulate proliferation,

477
00:28:55.364 --> 00:28:56.444
have

478
00:28:57.304 --> 00:29:01.104
pro-survival benefit. In micromets,

479
00:29:01.324 --> 00:29:05.014
where it's a new environment for these cancer cells, it need not be the

480
00:29:05.104 --> 00:29:09.024
case, but it could be. We need to really dissect that out in our liver

481
00:29:09.124 --> 00:29:12.814
models where we can manipulate the components of HSCs,

482
00:29:13.364 --> 00:29:15.584
NK cells, and CD8 positive T cells.

483
00:29:16.404 --> 00:29:16.984
Great, thank you.

484
00:29:22.844 --> 00:29:24.864
Hi, I'm Sandy Markowitz from Cleveland.

485
00:29:25.244 --> 00:29:27.944
Our lab developed SW33291.

486
00:29:29.444 --> 00:29:33.094
Just a comment that even at the initiation stage,

487
00:29:33.604 --> 00:29:37.244
the effects of PG2 are incredibly context dependent.

488
00:29:38.204 --> 00:29:41.944
So while it's absolutely true that Ray showed many years

489
00:29:41.984 --> 00:29:45.704
ago that administering PG2 to the APC

490
00:29:45.764 --> 00:29:47.924
mouse will accelerate tumor formation,

491
00:29:49.184 --> 00:29:52.924
we presented data last year that in the AOM DSS

492
00:29:53.024 --> 00:29:56.904
model, PG2 actually again reduces tumor formation.

493
00:29:57.644 --> 00:30:01.293
SoWhether that is immune dependent or

494
00:30:01.464 --> 00:30:05.204
not is unclear. But what is clear is that there are so

495
00:30:05.444 --> 00:30:09.384
many different pathways downstream of both

496
00:30:09.464 --> 00:30:11.064
COX-2 and PGDH,

497
00:30:11.964 --> 00:30:15.504
that you can get different outcomes depending on the context of which you

498
00:30:15.644 --> 00:30:17.284
tune the model.

499
00:30:18.544 --> 00:30:22.504
No, and I agree. And I think the liver, at least

500
00:30:22.804 --> 00:30:23.924
in the state that we're

501
00:30:24.824 --> 00:30:28.544
studying it in, in the non-inflamed liver, it'd be interesting to look in fatty

502
00:30:28.624 --> 00:30:29.054
livers,

503
00:30:30.364 --> 00:30:34.064
in the alcohol-damaged liver, we may come to different conclusions.

504
00:30:34.184 --> 00:30:34.464
But

505
00:30:35.784 --> 00:30:38.524
it's something to keep in mind. Thank you so much for the comment.

506
00:30:39.164 --> 00:30:40.324
Thanks for the very elegant work.

507
00:30:41.184 --> 00:30:44.824
So I think I see the red light flashing, so I think that

508
00:30:44.904 --> 00:30:47.864
indicates that I'm out of time, but I am the chair, so

509
00:30:48.764 --> 00:30:52.384
I do have a responsibility to introduce and moderate.

510
00:30:52.464 --> 00:30:55.964
So our next speaker is Professor Ruth

511
00:30:56.044 --> 00:30:59.604
Langley from the University College of London, who's a physician

512
00:30:59.704 --> 00:31:03.224
scientist and has played many important

513
00:31:03.324 --> 00:31:06.694
roles in elucidating a lot of the

514
00:31:06.694 --> 00:31:09.724
translational aspects of aspirin

515
00:31:10.524 --> 00:31:14.124
treatment in patients. Ruth, welcome to the

516
00:31:14.144 --> 00:31:15.944
podium.

517
00:31:26.424 --> 00:31:29.524
Good morning, and thank you for the introduction.

518
00:31:30.744 --> 00:31:34.364
I'm going to talk about platelet activation and inhibition

519
00:31:34.924 --> 00:31:38.684
and its relationship to aspirin and cancer prevention.

520
00:31:41.714 --> 00:31:45.664
These are my disclosures. I've received grant funding from Cancer

521
00:31:45.744 --> 00:31:49.464
Research UK for aspirin-related work, and the

522
00:31:49.504 --> 00:31:53.424
AdAspirin trial has received donated aspirin and placebo from

523
00:31:53.504 --> 00:31:54.044
Bayer.

524
00:31:58.144 --> 00:32:01.664
The history of aspirin and cancer, as we've heard,

525
00:32:01.804 --> 00:32:05.544
dates back many years. This is one of the first

526
00:32:05.664 --> 00:32:09.284
studies that was published in The Lancet over 50 years

527
00:32:09.304 --> 00:32:12.764
ago. It's a relatively simple experiment

528
00:32:13.284 --> 00:32:16.964
where cancer cells were injected into mice and half the

529
00:32:17.004 --> 00:32:19.724
mice were given aspirin in their drinking water.

530
00:32:20.574 --> 00:32:24.484
Those that received aspirin developed significantly

531
00:32:24.564 --> 00:32:28.484
fewer lung metastases, and I think if this was published

532
00:32:28.524 --> 00:32:32.124
today with a new drug, it would generate a lot of

533
00:32:32.184 --> 00:32:33.024
interest.

534
00:32:35.904 --> 00:32:39.224
This was then followed by many epidemiological

535
00:32:39.284 --> 00:32:42.644
studies looking at aspirin for primary

536
00:32:42.784 --> 00:32:43.584
prevention.

537
00:32:44.584 --> 00:32:47.964
This is some summary data that was put together

538
00:32:48.744 --> 00:32:52.624
around 2020. Over 200

539
00:32:52.804 --> 00:32:56.304
studies, both case control and cohort

540
00:32:56.444 --> 00:32:57.024
studies.

541
00:32:58.024 --> 00:33:01.904
The key findings were the aspirin reduces the risk

542
00:33:01.944 --> 00:33:05.824
of colorectal cancer and other GI cancers

543
00:33:05.864 --> 00:33:07.544
by about 30%.

544
00:33:08.644 --> 00:33:11.924
The estimates for other tumor types were around

545
00:33:11.964 --> 00:33:14.664
10% or more uncertain.

546
00:33:15.744 --> 00:33:19.564
But the key thing to note from these studies is that they were

547
00:33:19.664 --> 00:33:23.104
all evaluating low dose,

548
00:33:23.764 --> 00:33:27.734
somewhere between 75 and 325 milligrams

549
00:33:27.804 --> 00:33:31.504
of aspirin daily, and that's an antiplatelet

550
00:33:31.564 --> 00:33:35.124
dose rather than an anti-inflammatory dose,

551
00:33:35.644 --> 00:33:39.124
where you have to give the aspirin three or four times a day.

552
00:33:43.244 --> 00:33:47.044
The challenges, as we've just heard, are that the

553
00:33:47.104 --> 00:33:50.624
clinical trial results have been variable.

554
00:33:51.504 --> 00:33:55.304
There is good evidence that aspirin prevents

555
00:33:55.424 --> 00:33:59.034
Lynch syndrome cancers through the CAP-2 and

556
00:33:59.124 --> 00:34:02.924
CAP-3 trials, which were led by Professor Sir

557
00:34:03.004 --> 00:34:06.284
John Burn, which we heard about in the symposium

558
00:34:06.384 --> 00:34:07.164
yesterday.

559
00:34:08.064 --> 00:34:11.705
And importantly, the CAP-3 trial has

560
00:34:11.745 --> 00:34:15.263
shown that 100 milligrams of aspirin daily

561
00:34:15.844 --> 00:34:19.245
is as effective as 600 milligrams for

562
00:34:19.284 --> 00:34:20.884
preventing these tumors.

563
00:34:22.104 --> 00:34:25.924
But in the non-molecularly selected populations,

564
00:34:26.364 --> 00:34:30.205
such as the ASPREE trial, the results have not

565
00:34:30.284 --> 00:34:32.324
always been what we have expected.

566
00:34:35.765 --> 00:34:39.064
The effect of aspirin on the arachidonic pathway is well

567
00:34:39.225 --> 00:34:43.205
characterized as shown by the diagram, and this

568
00:34:43.284 --> 00:34:46.884
work has come both from the cancer field

569
00:34:47.104 --> 00:34:49.245
and from the cardiovascular field.

570
00:34:51.104 --> 00:34:54.665
Low dose daily aspirin inhibits COX-1,

571
00:34:55.265 --> 00:34:59.144
and the clinical effect is most marked in the

572
00:34:59.224 --> 00:35:02.964
anucleate platelet that can't resynthesize

573
00:35:03.084 --> 00:35:06.464
COX-1 and the effect lasts for the

574
00:35:06.504 --> 00:35:10.364
duration of the platelet life, which is about 10 days.

575
00:35:11.624 --> 00:35:15.234
You get subsequent reductions in prostaglandins and

576
00:35:15.284 --> 00:35:16.764
thromboxane A2,

577
00:35:17.744 --> 00:35:21.384
but again, as we've just heard, how that precisely

578
00:35:21.424 --> 00:35:24.864
links to cancer prevention has been less clear.

579
00:35:28.784 --> 00:35:31.064
And that got us to thinking about precision

580
00:35:31.164 --> 00:35:34.824
medicine and aspirin and cancer

581
00:35:34.904 --> 00:35:38.604
prevention. When we normally think about precision

582
00:35:38.644 --> 00:35:42.184
medicine, we think we start with

583
00:35:42.244 --> 00:35:46.154
enhanced knowledge of cancer biology, and we think that

584
00:35:46.204 --> 00:35:49.824
this will lead to a new or repurposed drug development

585
00:35:49.964 --> 00:35:53.384
program, ideally with a companion

586
00:35:53.464 --> 00:35:57.364
biomarker, and that will allow us to identify the

587
00:35:57.404 --> 00:36:01.144
individuals that are most likely to benefit and

588
00:36:01.224 --> 00:36:01.744
improved

589
00:36:01.824 --> 00:36:05.720
outcomes.When we put

590
00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:09.720
aspirin into this schema, we already have the drug.

591
00:36:10.660 --> 00:36:14.600
It's widely available and pretty well-tolerated.

592
00:36:15.540 --> 00:36:18.910
We also have substantial epidemiological

593
00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:22.540
evidence and some randomized evidence of

594
00:36:22.580 --> 00:36:23.940
improved outcomes.

595
00:36:26.400 --> 00:36:30.240
But there are several unanswered questions, particularly

596
00:36:30.700 --> 00:36:34.640
how does aspirin prevent cancer, and how can we

597
00:36:34.760 --> 00:36:38.540
identify those individuals most likely to benefit?

598
00:36:40.240 --> 00:36:44.050
And it was these questions that led us to

599
00:36:44.460 --> 00:36:48.440
forming what we've called the SPARC collaboration, and it's a

600
00:36:48.480 --> 00:36:52.360
collection of basic scientists, clinicians, patient

601
00:36:52.500 --> 00:36:55.660
advocates, pharmacologists, and trialists

602
00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.940
all working together, and I'm going to show you some of their

603
00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:01.460
work

604
00:37:02.260 --> 00:37:03.480
in the next slides.

605
00:37:07.080 --> 00:37:10.099
So I'm going to start with the mechanism of action.

606
00:37:11.040 --> 00:37:13.860
And I'm going to focus on two studies.

607
00:37:14.560 --> 00:37:18.320
The first one is work from the lab of

608
00:37:18.600 --> 00:37:22.160
Paola Patrigiani in the University of Chieti,

609
00:37:22.860 --> 00:37:26.720
and they were working with mice that have a specific deletion

610
00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:30.430
of the COX-1 gene in megakaryocytes and

611
00:37:30.560 --> 00:37:34.320
platelets, so they're a good model of low dose

612
00:37:34.400 --> 00:37:35.420
daily aspirin.

613
00:37:36.370 --> 00:37:39.680
And they crossed these mice with ApcMin mice,

614
00:37:40.460 --> 00:37:44.180
and what they found is the progeny developed fewer

615
00:37:44.620 --> 00:37:47.580
and smaller adenomas, highlighting

616
00:37:48.840 --> 00:37:52.680
the importance of platelet COX-1 activity in

617
00:37:52.720 --> 00:37:56.360
early carcinogenesis. What was also

618
00:37:56.440 --> 00:38:00.260
interesting about this study was that the adenomas that did

619
00:38:00.300 --> 00:38:04.180
develop had less COX-2, suggesting that

620
00:38:04.200 --> 00:38:08.130
COX-1 expression drives COX-2 induction in

621
00:38:08.180 --> 00:38:08.840
this model.

622
00:38:09.960 --> 00:38:13.800
And this also potentially explains how both

623
00:38:13.860 --> 00:38:17.220
low dose aspirin and selective COX-2

624
00:38:17.260 --> 00:38:21.160
inhibitors in clinical trials have been shown to

625
00:38:21.200 --> 00:38:24.240
prevent adenoma formation.

626
00:38:26.820 --> 00:38:30.680
The second study I want to focus on is the study

627
00:38:30.720 --> 00:38:34.500
that was previously mentioned from the laboratory of Rahul

628
00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:38.300
Roy Chowdhury at the University of Cambridge and

629
00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:40.300
published in "Nature" last year.

630
00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:44.680
This story starts from an in vivo mouse

631
00:38:44.760 --> 00:38:47.560
genetic screen, which was aimed at

632
00:38:47.640 --> 00:38:51.560
identifying the host regulators of cancer

633
00:38:51.600 --> 00:38:52.660
metastasis.

634
00:38:53.840 --> 00:38:57.600
The group was focused on RGF1 in T

635
00:38:57.700 --> 00:39:01.660
cells, which inhibits T cell immunity, and what they

636
00:39:01.740 --> 00:39:05.380
found was that it was regulated by the thromboxane

637
00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:08.740
receptor, which was an unexpected finding.

638
00:39:09.269 --> 00:39:13.190
And the reason that this was exciting was it linked for the

639
00:39:13.220 --> 00:39:17.100
first time the known pharmacological effects of

640
00:39:17.140 --> 00:39:20.620
once daily low dose aspirin, particularly reducing

641
00:39:20.660 --> 00:39:24.020
thromboxane A2 and cancer clearance.

642
00:39:24.700 --> 00:39:28.480
And it also, for the first time, implicated aspirin

643
00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:31.680
in a potential immune mechanism.

644
00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:41.040
So putting these two studies together, we have the

645
00:39:41.080 --> 00:39:44.440
hypothesis that the anticancer effects of

646
00:39:44.480 --> 00:39:47.329
aspirin are mediated and

647
00:39:47.560 --> 00:39:51.100
started through a reduction

648
00:39:51.500 --> 00:39:55.420
in platelet activation, and particularly the lowering

649
00:39:55.460 --> 00:39:57.060
of thromboxane A2.

650
00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:01.480
For primary prevention, there's a link between

651
00:40:01.520 --> 00:40:04.640
COX-1 and COX-2 in the inflammatory

652
00:40:04.660 --> 00:40:08.180
pathways, and for metastasis, the

653
00:40:08.220 --> 00:40:11.300
immune system is now implicated.

654
00:40:16.340 --> 00:40:20.080
So this led us to thinking, could platelet activation

655
00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:24.060
be a marker that we could use to find out who would

656
00:40:24.079 --> 00:40:25.860
benefit most from aspirin?

657
00:40:27.200 --> 00:40:30.480
Now you can measure platelet activation through a stable

658
00:40:30.760 --> 00:40:34.180
urinary metabolite of thromboxane A2,

659
00:40:34.880 --> 00:40:38.660
11-dehydro thromboxane B2, which is

660
00:40:38.740 --> 00:40:40.800
also known as UTXM.

661
00:40:42.020 --> 00:40:45.980
It's been studied extensively in cardiovascular disease,

662
00:40:46.700 --> 00:40:50.140
and you can see from the slide that it's raised in certain

663
00:40:50.240 --> 00:40:53.840
cardiovascular conditions, but it's also

664
00:40:53.960 --> 00:40:55.580
raised in

665
00:40:56.560 --> 00:40:59.900
and associated with cancer risk factors, for

666
00:40:59.960 --> 00:41:02.520
example, having a high BMI,

667
00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:06.100
diabetes, or in smokers.

668
00:41:11.220 --> 00:41:14.720
The ADD-ASPIRIN trial is a phase three basket

669
00:41:14.780 --> 00:41:18.100
trial. It's an ongoing adjuvant trial

670
00:41:18.460 --> 00:41:21.880
assessing aspirin after radical treatment,

671
00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:25.840
and the protocol includes four

672
00:41:26.380 --> 00:41:30.360
individually powered phase three trials in four different

673
00:41:30.420 --> 00:41:33.620
tumor types, one in breast cancer,

674
00:41:34.340 --> 00:41:38.220
colorectal cancer, gastroesophageal cancer,

675
00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:40.120
and prostate cancer.

676
00:41:41.360 --> 00:41:44.980
It's recruited over 10,000 participants from three

677
00:41:45.060 --> 00:41:46.180
different countries.

678
00:41:47.290 --> 00:41:51.000
The protocol also contains a run-in phase

679
00:41:51.720 --> 00:41:55.060
where everyone takes aspirin 100 milligrams

680
00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:58.580
daily for eight weeks to see if they tolerate

681
00:41:58.640 --> 00:42:02.360
aspirin and to see if they want to continue in the trial.

682
00:42:03.860 --> 00:42:07.600
If they do so, they are then randomized to taking aspirin

683
00:42:07.640 --> 00:42:11.120
100 milligrams, aspirin 300 milligrams,

684
00:42:11.580 --> 00:42:14.000
or a placebo for at least five

685
00:42:14.100 --> 00:42:17.970
years.And that framework has allowed

686
00:42:18.010 --> 00:42:21.900
us to study platelet activation at trial entry,

687
00:42:22.850 --> 00:42:26.690
after the run-in phase, and also during the randomization

688
00:42:26.770 --> 00:42:27.310
phase.

689
00:42:31.750 --> 00:42:33.800
So in this sub-study, which

690
00:42:36.230 --> 00:42:39.890
contains 700 participants from the ADD-Aspirin

691
00:42:39.990 --> 00:42:40.450
trial,

692
00:42:41.550 --> 00:42:44.630
we first were able to show that the

693
00:42:44.730 --> 00:42:48.490
UTXM levels were higher at baseline than

694
00:42:48.550 --> 00:42:52.190
healthy individuals. In the graph, the dotted

695
00:42:52.270 --> 00:42:55.790
line, which you can see at the bottom, is the levels that we would

696
00:42:55.810 --> 00:42:59.410
expect for healthy individuals based on previous studies.

697
00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:04.350
And this was a surprise because these were adjuvant patients

698
00:43:04.850 --> 00:43:05.310
who we

699
00:43:06.130 --> 00:43:09.730
are assuming are clear of their disease

700
00:43:10.070 --> 00:43:11.190
at trial entry.

701
00:43:12.210 --> 00:43:15.750
The other unexpected finding was that we saw a

702
00:43:15.890 --> 00:43:18.590
difference between the tumor types.

703
00:43:19.390 --> 00:43:22.670
So we found higher levels in the patients that had

704
00:43:22.730 --> 00:43:25.750
colorectal cancer and gastroesophageal

705
00:43:25.870 --> 00:43:29.710
cancer compared to breast cancer and prostate

706
00:43:29.770 --> 00:43:33.470
cancer. And that's an interesting observation given

707
00:43:34.170 --> 00:43:37.210
the higher levels in the tumors that arise from the

708
00:43:37.990 --> 00:43:41.920
GI tract, given the epidemiological data that

709
00:43:41.990 --> 00:43:43.060
I showed you earlier.

710
00:43:46.550 --> 00:43:50.350
We then went on to do multivariate analysis, and what we

711
00:43:50.410 --> 00:43:53.970
found was that the higher UTXM levels in the

712
00:43:54.030 --> 00:43:57.770
patients with the GI tumors could not be accounted

713
00:43:57.870 --> 00:44:01.650
for by recent surgery, chemotherapy, or

714
00:44:01.690 --> 00:44:03.310
any other clinical factor.

715
00:44:04.370 --> 00:44:08.350
And reassuringly, within this study, we found that

716
00:44:08.390 --> 00:44:12.130
the higher UTXM levels were associated with

717
00:44:12.210 --> 00:44:15.420
higher BMI, smoking, and raised

718
00:44:15.490 --> 00:44:16.210
inflammatory

719
00:44:17.290 --> 00:44:19.610
markers as we would expect.

720
00:44:24.470 --> 00:44:27.970
We also measured the UTXM levels over

721
00:44:28.110 --> 00:44:31.890
time and by randomized group. And in

722
00:44:31.930 --> 00:44:35.170
these plots, the blue line

723
00:44:35.590 --> 00:44:39.530
represents UTXM levels at baseline.

724
00:44:40.530 --> 00:44:44.210
The red line, where you can see it's suppressed in all the three

725
00:44:44.330 --> 00:44:48.030
plots, is at the end of the run-in, where everyone has been

726
00:44:48.090 --> 00:44:51.710
taking aspirin. And then we have the green line,

727
00:44:52.070 --> 00:44:54.650
which reflects the randomization phase.

728
00:44:55.290 --> 00:44:59.210
And if you look in the group that received placebo, you can see

729
00:44:59.270 --> 00:45:03.090
that the line has come up again in that placebo

730
00:45:03.190 --> 00:45:06.510
group, indicating persistent platelet

731
00:45:06.570 --> 00:45:09.970
activation in those recently diagnosed with

732
00:45:10.050 --> 00:45:10.709
cancer.

733
00:45:16.070 --> 00:45:19.810
Other groups have looked at UTXM levels

734
00:45:19.910 --> 00:45:23.270
and cancer outcomes. This is just one

735
00:45:23.350 --> 00:45:26.910
example. It's from the Framingham Heart Study.

736
00:45:27.710 --> 00:45:30.530
Here they had over 3,000 participants,

737
00:45:31.370 --> 00:45:34.990
and what they found were that there were higher UTXM levels at

738
00:45:35.110 --> 00:45:38.610
baseline were associated with reduced

739
00:45:38.650 --> 00:45:41.790
survival, the blue line on the graph.

740
00:45:42.250 --> 00:45:45.990
And what was interesting is this association was

741
00:45:46.010 --> 00:45:48.850
not just for all-cause mortality or

742
00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:52.850
cardiovascular mortality as you might expect, but it

743
00:45:52.890 --> 00:45:56.230
was also associated with cancer mortality.

744
00:45:57.010 --> 00:45:59.510
And there was an interesting editorial that

745
00:46:00.130 --> 00:46:04.010
accompanied this paper, which was entitled "Less

746
00:46:04.070 --> 00:46:06.030
Thromboxane, Longer Life."

747
00:46:12.330 --> 00:46:16.090
What has emerged recently is that in

748
00:46:16.150 --> 00:46:19.490
colorectal cancer, is that PIK3CA

749
00:46:19.530 --> 00:46:21.090
mutation status

750
00:46:21.950 --> 00:46:24.970
appears to be a biomarker of aspirin response.

751
00:46:25.720 --> 00:46:28.950
And this is data that you saw in the previous talk.

752
00:46:29.390 --> 00:46:33.070
It dates back to 2012. It's

753
00:46:33.130 --> 00:46:36.809
epidemiological data, and it was looking at aspirin

754
00:46:36.910 --> 00:46:40.050
use after a colorectal cancer diagnosis.

755
00:46:41.430 --> 00:46:45.290
And what was found that the improved colorectal

756
00:46:45.390 --> 00:46:49.070
cancer-specific survival and overall survival

757
00:46:49.470 --> 00:46:52.830
was seen with aspirin if the tumor had a

758
00:46:52.870 --> 00:46:56.790
mutation in the PIK3CA exon 9 and 20,

759
00:46:57.650 --> 00:47:00.850
but not if the tumor was wild type.

760
00:47:05.150 --> 00:47:08.910
This data and several other pieces of data

761
00:47:09.430 --> 00:47:12.950
led to several groups across the globe

762
00:47:13.070 --> 00:47:16.170
setting up adjuvant aspirin trials,

763
00:47:16.510 --> 00:47:18.650
particularly in colorectal cancer.

764
00:47:19.470 --> 00:47:22.530
I'm just going to orientate you on this slide.

765
00:47:22.950 --> 00:47:26.650
We have time across the bottom. Each of the solid

766
00:47:26.770 --> 00:47:30.160
